In[1]:
import pandas as pd
import requests
from io import StringIO
from IPython.display import display, Markdown

# URL of the Covid-19 CSV file
csv_url = "https://api.covidtracking.com/v1/states/daily.csv"  

# Step 1: Extract
response = requests.get(csv_url)

# Read the CSV with error handling
try:
    data = pd.read_csv(StringIO(response.text), on_bad_lines='warn') 
except Exception as e:
    print(f"An error occurred: {e}")

# Step 2: Transform
def transform_data(df):
    critical_columns = [
        "date", "state", "positive", "negative", 
        "totalTestResults", "hospitalizedCurrently", 
        "hospitalizedCumulative", "inIcuCurrently", 
        "onVentilatorCurrently", "recovered", "death"
    ]
    df = df[critical_columns].copy() 
    
    # Renaming for clarity
    rename_mapping = {
        "date": "Date",
        "state": "State",
        "positive": "Positive Cases",
        "negative": "Negative Cases",
        "totalTestResults": "Total Test Results",
        "hospitalizedCurrently": "Hospitalized Currently",
        "hospitalizedCumulative": "Hospitalized Cumulative",
        "inIcuCurrently": "ICU Currently",
        "onVentilatorCurrently": "On Ventilator Currently",
        "recovered": "Recovered",
        "death": "Deaths"
    }
    df.rename(columns=rename_mapping, inplace=True)

    return df




# Transform the data
transformed_data = transform_data(data)

# Step 3: Load (Display)
display(Markdown("# States Current and Historical Data for Covid-19 Tracking"))
display(transformed_data)

In[2]:
import pandas as pd

# Define chunk size (adjust based on your system's capacity)
chunk_size = 100000  # You can try smaller chunks if this is still too large

# Initialize an empty list to store processed chunks
processed_chunks = []

# Load and process the dataset in chunks
for chunk in pd.read_csv("https://storage.googleapis.com/covid19-open-data/v3/epidemiology.csv", chunksize=chunk_size):
    # Drop rows where 'new_confirmed' is 0.0
    chunk_cleaned = chunk[chunk['new_confirmed'] != 0.0]
    
    # Append the cleaned chunk to the list
    processed_chunks.append(chunk_cleaned)

# Concatenate all processed chunks into a single DataFrame
dataset = pd.concat(processed_chunks, ignore_index=True)

# Display the first few rows of the cleaned dataset
dataset.head()

Step 3: Aggregate the data to strictly monthly records

In[4]:
import pandas as pd

# Ensure 'Date' is in datetime format
dataset['Date'] = pd.to_datetime(dataset['Date'])

# Extract year and month for grouping
dataset['Year-Month'] = dataset['Date'].dt.to_period('M')

# Group by 'Location Key' and 'YearMonth', and sum up the relevant columns
monthly_totals = dataset.groupby(['Location Key', 'Year-Month']).agg({
    'New Confirmed': 'sum',
    'New Deceased': 'sum',
    'New Recovered': 'sum',
    'New Tested': 'sum',
    'Cumulative Confirmed': 'last',  # Keep the last cumulative value
    'Cumulative Deceased': 'last',
    'Cumulative Recovered': 'last',
    'Cumulative Tested': 'last'
}).reset_index()

# Display the first few rows of the aggregated dataset
display(monthly_totals)

import pandas as pd

# Assuming 'monthly_totals' is your original DataFrame
# Define valid state abbreviations
state_abbreviations = [
    'AL', 'AK', 'AZ', 'AR', 'CA', 'CO', 'CT', 'DE', 'FL', 'GA',
    'HI', 'ID', 'IL', 'IN', 'IA', 'KS', 'KY', 'LA', 'ME', 'MD',
    'MA', 'MI', 'MN', 'MS', 'MO', 'MT', 'NE', 'NV', 'NH', 'NJ',
    'NM', 'NY', 'NC', 'ND', 'OH', 'OK', 'OR', 'PA', 'RI', 'SC',
    'SD', 'TN', 'TX', 'UT', 'VT', 'VA', 'WA', 'WV', 'WI', 'WY'
]

# Create a filter pattern for US location keys
filter_pattern = '|'.join([f'US_{state}' for state in state_abbreviations])

# Filter the DataFrame for location keys that exactly match the pattern
filtered_data = monthly_totals[monthly_totals['Location Key'].isin([f'US_{state}' for state in state_abbreviations])]

# Check the unique location codes and their count
unique_location_codes = filtered_data['Location Key'].unique()
print(f'Unique Location Codes: {unique_location_codes}')
print(f'Number of Unique Location Codes: {len(unique_location_codes)}')

# Update the dataset to only include the filtered data
dataset = filtered_data
dataset.reset_index(drop=True, inplace=True)

# Display the first few rows of the new filtered dataset
display(dataset)

import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
import seaborn as sns

# Total confirmed cases by state
total_cases = dataset.groupby('Location Key')['Cumulative Confirmed'].max().reset_index()

# Remove "US_" prefix from the Location Key for y-axis labels
total_cases['State Abbreviation'] = total_cases['Location Key'].str.replace('US_', '')

# Sort values for better visualization
total_cases = total_cases.sort_values(by='Cumulative Confirmed', ascending=False)

plt.figure(figsize=(14, 8))
sns.barplot(x='Cumulative Confirmed', y='State Abbreviation', data=total_cases, palette='viridis')
plt.title('Total Confirmed COVID-19 Cases by State')
plt.xlabel('Total Confirmed Cases (Ten million)')
plt.ylabel('State Abbreviation')  # Update the label to reflect the abbreviation
plt.tight_layout()
plt.show()

# List of line styles to choose from
line_styles = ['-', '--', '-.', ':']

# Line plot for monthly trends of confirmed cases
plt.figure(figsize=(18, 12))  # Increased size for a much larger plot
num_states = monthly_totals['Location Key'].nunique()
colors = sns.color_palette("husl", num_states)  # Using the Husl color palette for distinct colors

# Loop through each unique state to plot its trend
for i, state in enumerate(monthly_totals['Location Key'].unique()):
    state_data = monthly_totals[monthly_totals['Location Key'] == state]
    plt.plot(state_data['Year-Month'], state_data['Cumulative Confirmed'], 
             label=state.replace('US_', ''), color=colors[i % num_states], 
             linestyle=line_styles[i % len(line_styles)], linewidth=2)

plt.title('Monthly Trend of Total Confirmed COVID-19 Cases by State', fontsize=16)
plt.xlabel('Year-Month', fontsize=14)
plt.ylabel('Total Confirmed Cases (Ten Million)', fontsize=14)
plt.xticks(rotation=45, fontsize=12)  # Rotate x-axis labels for better readability
plt.legend(title='State Abbreviation', bbox_to_anchor=(1.05, 1), loc='upper left', fontsize=12)
plt.tight_layout()
plt.show()
